column521: To me the most benefical thing was to look at the options orange had and to work back from there. I looked at what others would chose to be their best move and worked off of that.

If the two quantities in one row were higher than those in the other row I immediately chose that row. If the quantities in     both rows were fairly equal I looked to see if the next player had one row with two high values and so on. If all players     had fairly equal values in both rows I looked at what the first player chose to decide what the last player would choose and went backwards from there. I was assuming  and hoping  that each player would think the same.

I played based on the potential choices of the last player who would pick a certain choice based on the decision of the first player. Once observing that  there is dominoe effect where each player pick the best possible choices given the first player and the potential choices of the last player
I looked at the color after me and then what the color before the next one chose to see the optimal amount that I could possibly obtain

If I was the first player  I would first look to see how the numbers were placed in my box. If the top two are bigger than the bottom two  I chose the first option. It they werent  then I looked how first choice would affect the last choice  then second to last  then second  then ultimately what I would get. I would do that for the second choice and then compare which higher number I could receive. I would choose the one I would get the higher number with. If I were second or third  I would follow a similar strategy. If I was second  I would see how the first choice affected the last  then second to last  then me. Then  I would compare between the two choices and choose the higher one.

I always looked at what the person after me was most likely to choose (based on the person after them  as well). Sometimes it didn't work too well because some people have terrible logic and choose Xb (10 and 30) instead of Yb (12 and 32) even though Yb has a much higher average output. I noticed that being second generally put me in the worst position in terms of returning a higher yield.
I went from Red backwards and guessed what each player would choose so that I could get the most amount possible.

When I was the first to chose  I try both X and Y in my head to see how much each of them will benefit me and then chose the one benefit me more. Go to the last Payoff 2X2 square first to see which one would the participant chose to maximize his or her benefit according to my choice  and repeat the procedure till I know my own profit. It would be even easier when I was not the first  especially when I was the last to choose.
I worked backwards  using the response of the first person to determine those of others  assuming that the others were also trying to maximize their earnings.

I tried to anticipate what the others would choose while maximizing each person's number of points. For example  if I was 3rd to last  I would have looked at the last player's options and see what the first player chose. Then I would pick the choice that would enable the last player to have the most money and me  the most money out of my possible selections. Sometimes  I also decided just to pick the row that had the maximum values  for example if in one row the values were much higher than the others in all choices  then it was easy to just click that one. |  | I have heard of game theory before but have not taken any courses...I see how the numbers are gamed/strategized somewhat  and so I try to pick my row/column that will help everyone (and myself) get the most points.
I will guess what other players will do. Since everyone wants to gain the most benefit  they will all consider each others' situation  and find a best way.

I chose to always be moderate  and assumed others would too. If everyone was moderate together  we could do fairly well. Chosing the higher number usually came with higher risk  and only in some case where everyone chose the higher number would we all benefit.
